05992nam a22009135i 9780824881702DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20192020hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248817027 a10.1515/97808248817022doi  a(DE-B1597)518492  a(OCoLC)1149519985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aNK8875 7aART0190002bisacsh04a746.0958  aNF 8670qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/125333:1 aGasparini, Mariachiara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTranscending Patterns :bSilk Road Cultural and Artistic Interactions through Central Asian Textile Images /cMariachiara Gasparini; ed. by Kieko Matteson, Anand A. Yang. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (278 p.) :b20 color, 27 b&w illustrations, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on the Global Past00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Terms, Transliterations, and Translations -- tIntroduction: A Medieval Matrix -- tCHAPTER 1. The Development of Central Asian Textile Imagery -- tCHAPTER 2. The Sino-Sogdian Matrix and Its Preservation -- tCHAPTER 3. The Adaptation of Ancient Central Asian Patterns -- tCHAPTER 4. A Kinship of Images -- tCONCLUSION. A Step Away from the Renaissance -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Transcending Patterns: Silk Road Cultural and Artistic Interactions through Central Asian Textiles, Mariachiara Gasparini investigates the origin and effects of a textile-mediated visual culture that developed at the heart of the Silk Road between the seventh and fourteenth centuries. Through the analysis of the Turfan Textile Collection in the Museum of Asian Art in Berlin and more than a thousand textiles held in collections worldwide, Gasparini discloses and reconstructs the rich cultural entanglements along the Silk Road, between the coming of Islam and the rise of the Mongol Empire, from the Tarim to Mediterranean Basin. Exploring in detail the iconographic transfer between different agents and different media from Central Asian caves to South Italian churches, the author depicts and describes the movement and exchange of portable objects such as sculpture, wall painting, and silk fragments across the Asian continent and across the ages.Gasparini’s history offers critical perspectives that extend far beyond an outmoded notion of “Silk Road studies.” Her cross-media work shows readers how certain material cultures are connected not only by the physical routes they take but also because of the meanings and interpretations these objects engage in various places. Transcending Patterns is at once art history, material and visual cultural history, Asian studies, conservatory studies, and linguistics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArt, Asian. 0aDesign. 0aHistory. 0aTextile designzAsia, Central. 0aTextile fabricszAsia, Central. 0aTrade routesxSocial aspectszAsia, Central. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aMatteson, Kieko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYang, Anand A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2019z9783110605747oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 20